{
  "answer": "**Bang-E-Dara Part 1** (Allama Iqbal) contains multiple apostrophes to inanimate or abstract objects, such as the candle (*shama*), anguish of love (*dard-e-ishq*), fantasy/imagination (*khayal*), and the wheel of time.[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\n**Bang-E-Dara Part 2** (Allama Iqbal) addresses the candle.[^5]\n\n**Diwan-E-Zauq** (Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq) apostrophizes the candle.[^6]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain clear rhetorical apostrophes to inanimate objects (as opposed to divine beings, heroes, or persons). Old English poems like *Andreas* feature frequent vocatives (\"O hero,\" etc.), but these address animate figures or the Lord/God, not inanimates.[^7] Searches across the Indic *smṛti* texts, French treatises, and other poetry yielded no matches.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/40-shama/translation/#p-89fef5).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/17-dard-e-ishq/translation/#p-6d19d8).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-417cdf).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/40-shama/translation/#p-28baca).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/03-misaal-e-partav-e-mai-tawaf-e-jaam-karte-hain/translation/#p-1a93ca).\n\n[^6]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/05-ae-zauq-waqt-naale-ke-rakh-le-jigar-pe-haath/translation/#p-b7e0c9).\n\n[^7]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-58182e).",
